Moreover, the binding energy of S 2p changed from 162.0 eV to 164.3 eV after being treated with Hg2+ (Fig. 1h vs. 
                        Fig. 6d), indicating a decrease in the negative charge density on the S atoms. Therefore, Hg-S bonds might have formed, which could lead to the electron transfer from S to Hg2+ 
                        [46]. More direct evidence for the formation of Hg-S bonds can be observed in the S 2p high-resolution spectrum as displayed in Fig. 6h. However, the constitution of the CS bond could not be observed in Fig. 6h, suggesting that the electron-withdrawing CS bond has broken down after reacting with Hg2+. This reaction may increase the electron cloud density of N 1s, resulting in a decrease in the binding energy, which is consistent with the results in Fig. 6g. Additionally, the high-resolution XPS spectrum of Hg 4f consists of two typical peaks at 100.9 eV (Hg 4f7/2
                        ) and 105.0 eV (Hg 4f5/2
                        ) (Fig. 6i), indicating that mercury exists in the form of Hg2+, not in elemental or mercurous forms [43].
